        <h3 id="group-by-ordering">Ordering Grouped Collections</h3>
        
        <p>
            We can order the collections prior to grouping using the LINQ <NavLink href="blogs/using-linq-orderby-to-sort-data" Match="NavLinkMatch.All">OrderBy</NavLink>. 
            But if we want to order the collection after grouping we need to use <ContentHighlight>into</ContentHighlight> and <ContentHighlight>select</ContentHighlight> to make this happen in 
            Query Syntax and <ContentHighlight>select</ContentHighlight> in Method Syntax.
        </p>

        <CodeSnippet CssClass="language-csharp">
List&lt;Product&gt; products = GetProducts();

//Method Syntax
List&lt;IGrouping&lt;string, Product&gt;&gt; result = products
                                           .GroupBy(product =&gt; product.Color)
                                           .OrderBy(group =&gt; group.Key)
                                           .Select(group =&gt; group)
                                           .ToList();
                    
//Query Syntax
List&lt;IGrouping&lt;string, Product&gt;&gt; result = (from product in products
                                           group product by product.Color into group
                                           order by group.Key
                                           select group)
                                           .ToList();
        </CodeSnippet>

        

        <h3 id="group-by-filtering">Filtering Grouped Collections</h3>
        
        <p>
            We can filter the collections after grouping using the LINQ <NavLink href="blogs/using-linq-where-to-filter-data" Match="NavLinkMatch.All">Where</NavLink>. 
            This is similar to <ContentHighlight>Having</ContentHighlight> clause in <abbr title="Structured Query Language">SQL</abbr>.
        </p>

        <CodeSnippet CssClass="language-csharp">
List&lt;Product&gt; products = GetProducts();

//Method Syntax
List&lt;IGrouping&lt;string, Product&gt;&gt; result = products
                                           .GroupBy(product =&gt; product.Color)
                                           .OrderBy(group =&gt; group.Key)
                                           .Where(group =&gt; group.Count() &gt; 1)
                                           .Select(group =&gt; group)
                                           .ToList();
                    
//Query Syntax
List&lt;IGrouping&lt;string, Product&gt;&gt; result = (from product in products
                                           group product by product.Color into group
                                           order by group.Key
                                           where group.Count() &gt; 1
                                           select group)
                                           .ToList();
        </CodeSnippet>

        

        <h3 id="summary">Summary</h3>

        <p>
            In this article we learn't how to group data in collections using <ContentHighlight>GroupBy</ContentHighlight>. This allows you to group elements in collection based on a 
            specified key resulting in <ContentHighlight>IGrouping&lt;Key, Object&gt;</ContentHighlight> collection. All these can be used with any 
            <ContentHighlight>IEnumerable</ContentHighlight> or <ContentHighlight>IQueryable</ContentHighlight> types.
        </p>
